The paper presents a novel algorithm for rounding packing integer programs based on multidimensional Brownian motion, which is a technique commonly used in computational geometry and optimization. This suggests that the paper may belong to sub-categories related to algorithms, computational geometry, and optimization. Specifically, cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.CC (computational complexity), and cs.CG (computational geometry) are likely sub-categories given the algorithmic nature of the paper. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of discrepancy-based arguments, which are commonly used in information theory and coding theory, suggesting that cs.IT (information theory) may also be a relevant sub-category.
